post_text:
Parents,

The ADPH has updated Back to School guidelines for COVID-19. If your child develops a new cough, loss of taste or smell, or has shortness of breath please do not send him or her to school. He should see his or her Health Care Provider. If your child has flu symptoms, vomiting, diarrhea or fever he or she should stay home until better for 24 hours with no medication (for those symptoms) and see their Health Care Provider if these last more than 72 hours. If you are in doubt about whether to send your child to school or not please contact your school nurse.

Thank you for being diligent.

Rhonda Bishop RN, MSN
rbishop@boazk12.org

post_text:
In order to establish new routines and procedures, Boaz City School will follow a staggered start for the first six days of school (August 20, 21, 24, 25, 26, 27).

BES & CES groups will be released with class postings on Monday and via a letter sent home to parents.

BES Pre-K will have a staggered start beginning Monday, August 24.

BIS, BMS, and BHS groups will be as follows:

Students whose last names begin with A-M will attend school on August 20, 24 and 26 (Thursday, Monday, Wednesday).

Students whose last names begin with N-Z will attend school on August 21, 25, and 27 (Friday, Tuesday, Thursday).

All students will attend school on Friday, August 28.

shared_text:
Rick Karle WVTM 13
July 29 at 4:29 AM ·

I love this!

Ranai Ortega is a freshman lineman at Boaz High School. A young man of modest means, Ranai’s mode of transportation has been his beloved bicycle. But when Ranai’s bike broke, he didn’t have a way home from practice.

Get this: Ranai’s teammates heard about his troubles and decided to pitch in their own money to buy a Ranai a new bike!
The players pooled their money, went shopping and picked out the bike themselves (just click on video below to watch)!

I’m so proud of the kids from Boaz!
During what has been a difficult time, these kids stepped up and gave from their hearts.
Be sure to give your best to Ranai, his teammates and coach Jeremy Sullivan.

Thanks to AD Patrick Williams for the video.

post_text:
Fall sports athletes and parents (football, volleyball, XC, swimming, cheer):

*Many of you have registered on Dragonfly, completed the medical info, and signed all your forms electronically.

*Some of you have registered on Dragonfly and did not complete the medical info and sign your forms electronically.

*Many have not registered yet at all.

*Also, many have not gotten physicals yet.

All of this must be completed by the first day of fall practice, July 27. If you need guidance in how to do this, see the attachment or come by Boaz High School Monday-Friday 8:00-3:00, and Coach Williams will help you. Physical forms are also attached here.

*If you are an incoming 7th grade athlete, you must complete the online Sportsmanship module. Here are the directions:

1. Log on to NFHSLearn.com.

2. Create an account.

3. Search for the Sportsmanship course.

4. Go through and complete the course.

5. When you are finished, save your completion certificate and email it to Coach Williams at pwilliams@boazk12.org.

post_text:
In an effort to make logins easier (especially for our younger students) and facilitate improved online communication between teachers and students, we are changing student usernames/email addresses to a new format. All existing student email and documents stored in Google will remain and will be available after the change.

All students returning in the fall should have received an email letting them know their new username/email address. The new name took effect on Monday, June 8, and will affect Google, Office365, Clever, etc.

The new standard is pretty simple, first name (as it is in iNow), and initials. If there is a duplicate, a number (1,2,3) is added to the username.
Examples are:

John Doe = JohnD@boazk12.org
John David Doe = JohnDD@boazk12.org
John Daniel Doe = JohnDD1@boazk12.org
John David Doe-Smith = JohnDDS@boazk12.org

Any student who did not receive the email can email the Technology Helpdesk (helpdesk@boazk12.org) before the effective date. You must contact the helpdesk from your school Gmail account.

Every 10 years, the U.S. census is sent to every household in the country. It contains 10 simple questions. And it only takes 6 minutes. The results of the 2020 Census will help determine how hundreds of billions of dollars in federal funding flows into communities every year for the next decade. This impacts health care, schools, roads, job opportunities, and more.

If you haven't completed the census for your household yet, get started here: 2020census.gov/en.html

post_text:
Parents/Guardians,

We have had a few parents request that their child be able to take Accelerated Reading test(s) from home while we are away from school. We have worked with the company to make this happen. IT IS NOT REQUIRED, but please feel free to let your child read and test on books as we are away from campuses. Your student should know his/her login and password already. If he/she does not, your child can click to recover password from the login screen. Again, this is an optional activity and not required, so please do not panic if your child cannot login. Simply have your child keep up with the books he/she has read, and then he/she can test upon the return to campus.

We are attaching student reading logs to help your child keep track of his/her reading (English and Spanish).

Here is the link to the correct website for login (please note that you do NOT need to google AR, as you might get directed to an incorrect login page):

https://hosted283.renlearn.com/1876921

post_text:
BCSS Community:

Earlier this evening Governor Kay Ivey issued a “State of Emergency” in the state of Alabama due to the Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19). Although the “State of Emergency” begins immediately for the state, our state public schools will continue with classes until the end of the school day on Wednesday, March 18, 2020. At that time all public schools will remained closed until Monday, April 6, 2020. State Superintendent Dr. Eric Mackey stated that the ALSDE along with other governmental agencies will re-evaluate the situation during the time off and will provide guidance before the closure period ends.

All schools, offices, and campuses will be closed from Thursday, March 19 through Friday, April 3.

We will continue to work in conjunction with state and local agencies to receive the most up to date information regarding COVID-19 and the “State of Emergency.”

Dr. H.

Corley Elementary School was selected as a 2019 CLAS School of Distinction! I am very proud of our students, faculty, and parents!

This award recognizes school programs that serve as outstanding educational models for other schools in Alabama.

The CLAS Banner School program was created in 2001 to recognize schools in Alabama that showcase outstanding programs and service to students. This year 189 schools were nominated for the prestigious recognition with thirty schools selected as the 2019 CLAS Schools of Distinction.
